This page describes how to create and format pages on {{SITENAME}}.

== Creating a page ==

To create a new page, type the page name in the wiki search bar, then click '''Create the page''' in the search results. Alternatively, navigate directly to the URL <code><nowiki>https://aiinterpretability.miraheze.org/wiki/Page Name</nowiki></code> and click '''Create''' at the top.

== Page structure ==

Every article page follows this layout:

<pre>
<onlyinclude>
'''[[Article Title]]''' summary paragraph with inline <ref> citations.
</onlyinclude>

Author/publication metadata (e.g., "It is a 2023 paper by ...").

== References ==

<references />

== Created by ==

* Burny (links...).

[[Category:Category Name]]
</pre>

=== How it works ===

* <code><nowiki><onlyinclude></nowiki></code> wraps only the summary so category index pages can transclude a short description. Author and publication metadata goes after the closing <code><nowiki></onlyinclude></nowiki></code> tag so it does not appear in transclusions.
* The first bold mention of the article's own title in the summary must be a wikilink so it is clickable when transcluded on index pages: <code><nowiki>'''[[Page Name]]'''</nowiki></code>.
* The references section comes after the metadata.
* The category assignment is always the last line of the page.

== Adding a page to the category index ==

After creating a page, edit the corresponding category index page (e.g., [[:Category:Highlighted work|Highlighted work]]) and add a transclusion line:

<pre>
* {{:Article Title}}
</pre>

Because articles use <code><nowiki><onlyinclude></nowiki></code>, only the summary paragraph is pulled in. This keeps index pages automatically up to date with article content.

Also add the page to the Pages section of the [[Main Page]].

== Reference and citation format ==

References use Wikipedia-style Citation Style 1 (CS1) plain-text formatting inside <code><nowiki><ref></nowiki></code> tags. Use periods to separate fields. Titles of articles and pages go in double quotes, linked to the URL. Titles of journals, websites, and conference proceedings go in italics.

=== Examples ===

'''Web page:'''

<pre>
<ref>Last, First (YYYY-MM-DD). [https://example.com "Title"]. ''Website''.</ref>
</pre>

'''arXiv paper:'''

<pre>
<ref>Last1, First1; Last2, First2 (YYYY). [https://arxiv.org/abs/ID "Title"]. arXiv:[https://arxiv.org/abs/ID ID].</ref>
</pre>

'''Journal article:'''

<pre>
<ref>Last1, First1; Last2, First2 (YYYY). [https://doi.org/DOI "Title"]. ''Journal''. '''Vol'''(Issue): Pages. doi:[https://doi.org/DOI DOI].</ref>
</pre>

'''Conference paper:'''

<pre>
<ref>Last1, First1; Last2, First2 (YYYY). [https://url "Title"]. ''Conference Name''. pp. Pages.</ref>
</pre>

'''Wiki/forum page:'''

<pre>
<ref>[https://example.com "Title"]. ''Site Name''.</ref>
</pre>

=== Rules ===

* Author names use <code>Last, First</code> format. Multiple authors are separated by semicolons.
* For 4 or more authors, list the first three and use <code>et al.</code>.
* Dates: <code>YYYY-MM-DD</code> for web pages with specific dates, <code>YYYY</code> for papers and journals.
* Volume numbers in bold: <code><nowiki>'''42'''</nowiki></code>.
* Use named refs when citing the same source multiple times: <code><nowiki><ref name="name">...</ref></nowiki></code> and <code><nowiki><ref name="name" /></nowiki></code>.
* When quoting text word-for-word from a source, wrap it in quotation marks with the source citation immediately after.

== Formatting conventions ==

* '''Bold''' (<code><nowiki>'''...'''</nowiki></code>) is used to introduce key terms and abbreviations on first mention.
* Level 2 headings (<code><nowiki>== ... ==</nowiki></code>) only â€” level 1 is reserved for the page title.
* Blank lines separate sections and structural elements; do not use multiple consecutive blank lines.
* When linking to a category from content without adding the page to that category, use the colon prefix: <code><nowiki>[[:Category:Name|Display Text]]</nowiki></code>.

